replies.bodyText:
Right, but we already have a logical block for determining the state, and we're already doing half the check done here in that block. We don't want to separate those blocks if we can avoid it:
if (pool.getDerivedProduct() != null) {
  // existing code as above
}
else if (existingPool.getDerivedProduct() != null) {
  productsChanged = true;
}

The previous code did work based on the null value (implicitly via encapsulation violations), so it had to do them there. Since we don't need to worry about that, we can safely just pass through whatever value is returned by getDerivedProduct, so long as our productsChanged variable is in the right state by the time we get there; we don't even need the additional null check, nor the warning comment block, anymore

timeline.bodyText:
This works, but still kinda violates the separation from the original implementation. Also, why did the access change?
In the interest of time, this is kind of what I was suggesting:
private boolean checkForChangedDerivedProducts(Pool pool, Pool existingPool, Map<String, Product> changedProducts) {

  boolean dpChanged = false;
  Product existingDerived = existingPool.getDerivedProduct();
  Product incomingDerived = pool.getDerivedProduct();

  if (incomingDerived != null) {
    dpChanged = (existingDerived == null) ||
      (existingDerived.getId() != null && !existingDerived.getId().equals(incomingDerived.getId())) ||
      (changedProducts != null && changedProducts.containsKey(existingDerived.getId()));
  }
  else {
    dpChanged = existingDerived != null;
  }

  if (dpChanged) {
    existingPool.setDerivedProduct(incomingDerived);
  }

  return dpChanged;
}

This still keeps the evaluation in one block, and the action to take on that evaluation result in another.

